org.qbroker.common

Class IndexedXQueue

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.qbroker.common.IndexedXQueue
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    XQueue

    public class IndexedXQueue
extends java.lang.Object
implements XQueue
    IndexedXQueue implements XQueue as a FIFO storage with circular array for tracking and transaction support.

    All cells in an XQueue line up in a circle implemented by an array. The cells on the same status always stay together in a group. Therefore the circle is divided into five segments of arcs. There are five marks separating those five arcs, ie, the five different groups of cells. Head divides taken cells and occupied cells. Tail separates occupied cells and reserved cells. Lead divides taken cells and empty cells. Mark separates reserved cells and empty cells. Cusp separates collected empty cells and the rest empty cells.

    Any object can be added to a cell of the XQueue. Once the cell is occupied, its overwriteability is determined by the instantiation parameter, overwriteable. By default, overwriteable is set to true so that the object in a cell is replacible during the operation of remove or putback. In this case, the application will have control on if to keep or reset the object. It is recommended to reset the object to null at the operation of remove and no change at the operation of putback. This way, the object will be de-referenced from the XQueue after it is removed. If overwriteable is set to false at the instantiation, the object will be reset to null at the operation of remove and no change at the operation of putback no matter what application does. This way, application has no way to replace the object in a cell unless it adds a new object to the cell.

    Sometimes, applications do need to use overwriteability to feedback new or same objects upstream. But this has a side effect. If the application has not reset the object to null, the object will not be gabbage collectible. It is OK if the capacity of the XQueue is small. But if it is large, it will cause object leek. If this is the choice, please make sure to de-reference the object once it is collected by the application. To de-reference the object, just add a null to the cell and remove it immediately.

    capacity -- maximum number of cells in the queue
    size -- number of the new and taken objects in the queue
    depth -- number of new objects in the queue
    watermark -- size + number of reserved cells
    collectible -- number of empty cells that have not been collected yet
    count -- number of objects taken out of the queue since last reset
    mtime -- timestamp of the reset on the queue
    status -- status of a cell or the object
    id -- the id of a cell or the object


    It is MT-Safe and has transaction control on retreiving.
